SuperMap tutorial

In this tutorial, we demonstrate how to use SuperMap for integrative analyses of unpaired single-cell multimodal data. Here, we showcase an example of integrating protein and ATAC modality. We use an ASAP-seq dataset downloaded from GEO (accession ID: GSE156478), which contains antibody-derived tag measurements for 227 proteins along with genome-wide chromatin accessibility profiles.

Necessary packages

To run this vignette, please ensure that the following packages are installed:

library(SuperMap)
library(Seurat)
library(Signac)
library(GenomicRanges)
library(GenomeInfoDb)
library(EnsDb.Hsapiens.v86)

Stage 1: Data Preparation

We begin by loading the downloaded data, which includes ADT and scATAC-seq measurements.

## Read data from the file
atac_count = readRDS('ASAP_data/atac_count.RDS')
adt_matrix = readRDS('ASAP_data/adt_matrix.RDS')

First, we create separate Seurat objects for the ADT and ATAC data, and then perform preprocessing for each modality.

adt_seurat = CreateSeuratObject(counts = t(adt_matrix),assay = 'ADT')

chrom_assay <- CreateChromatinAssay(
  counts = atac_count,
  sep = c("-", "-"),
  fragments = "ASAP_data/GSM4732109_CD28_CD3_control_ASAP_fragments.tsv.gz")
## Computing hash
atac_seurat <- CreateSeuratObject(counts = chrom_assay,assay = "ATAC")

Next, we perform data normalization and dimensional reduction for visualization, following the Seurat workflow. If you are unfamiliar with this workflow, please refer to their official tutorial.

adt_seurat = NormalizeData(adt_seurat)
## Normalizing layer: counts
adt_seurat = ScaleData(adt_seurat)
## Centering and scaling data matrix
adt_seurat = RunPCA(adt_seurat,features = rownames(adt_seurat),verbose = FALSE)
adt_seurat = RunUMAP(adt_seurat,dims = 1:50)

At this point, we have obtained two preprocessed Seurat objectsone for each modalitywhich are ready for the subsequent computational analyses.

Stage 2: Meta-cell construction

In practice, single-cell data are highly sparse and noisy, with an inherently low signal-to-noise ratio. This poses challenges for both model fitting and imputation, making it difficult for the model to capture reliable predictive signals. To address this, SuperMap adopts meta-cell partitioning strategy, a widely used approach to enhance the signal-to-noise ratio in single-cell data by aggregating closely similar cells into meta-cells. For more details, please refer to our paper. Next, we demonstrate how to construct the meta-cell data.

## The resolution parameter can be adjusted flexibly, as it determines the graining level of the resulting meta-cells. Meta-cell graining levels within a reasonable range (25105) are generally feasible. For more details, please refer to our paper.

adt_seurat = metacell_construct(object = adt_seurat, resolution = 15, graph.name = 'ADT_snn')

atac_seurat = metacell_construct(object = atac_seurat, resolution = 15, graph.name = 'ATAC_snn')

metacell_adt <- metacell_matrix_ADT(object = adt_seurat,cluster.name = "seurat_clusters")
metacell_atac <- metacell_matrix_ATAC(object = atac_seurat,cluster.name = "seurat_clusters")

At this point, we obtained metacell-level data for model fitting.

Stage 3: Computing peak-gene distance

SuperMap incorporates genomic proximity as prior knowledge to regularize the model. Therefore, we need to compute the genomic distances between protein-coding genes in the ADT modality and peaks in the ATAC modality. As a first step, we convert the protein names to their corresponding gene names.

rna_protein_conversion = read.csv(file = 'ASAP_data/rna_protein_correspondence.txt',header = FALSE, sep = ',')

adt_name = sub("^ADT-", "", colnames(metacell_adt))
colnames(metacell_adt) = adt_name
rna_protein_conversion = rna_protein_conversion[rna_protein_conversion$V2 %in% adt_name,]
metacell_adt = metacell_adt[,rna_protein_conversion$V2]
colnames(metacell_adt) = rna_protein_conversion$V1

gene_annotation = read.table('~/pbmc_pair_cpm/GRCh38_cellranger2020.gene_location.txt',sep = ' ',header = TRUE)   ## Read the genomic coordinates of all genes.

supermap_data = gene_peak_distance(rna = metacell_adt, atac = metacell_atac,gene_annotation = gene_annotation)

Stage 4: Model fitting for estimating cross-modal mappings

At this stage, we fit the model to learn the cross-modal mappings using the preprocessed data generated above.

learned_mappings = supermap(input_data = supermap_data)

The returned results include both the models convergence information and the estimated parameters. We first visualize the convergence curve from this run to examine the iteration process.

loss = learned_mappings$convergence
loss = as.data.frame(loss)

colnames(loss) = c('residual','objective')
loss$iter = c(1:nrow(loss))

plot(loss$objective)

We observed that the objective function steadily converged over iterations.

Stage 4: Imputating missing modality

After estimating B, we proceed to impute the missing (unmeasured) modality profiles in unpaired data for subsequent analyses. For imputation, SuperMap provides options at both meta-cell and single-cell resolution to accommodate different downstream analysis tasks. Below, we demonstrate how to predict protein abundance from chromatin accessibility.

## Meta-cell imputation
imputation_metacell = imputation(supermap_data = supermap_data, learned_mappings = learned_mappings, atac_data = atac_seurat, resolution = 'meta-cell')

##Single-cell imputation
imputation_singlecell = imputation(supermap_data = supermap_data, learned_mappings = learned_mappings, atac_data = atac_seurat, resolution = 'single-cell')
## Computing nearest neighbor graph
## Computing SNN

The imputed profiles enable a wide range of downstream analyses of unpaired data, including cell annotation, diagonal integration, regulatory inference, and trajectory analysis, thereby providing valuable biological insights. Next, we visualize the imputed expression patterns of several representative marker genes to facilitate cell annotation.

cell_umap = atac_seurat@reductions$umap@cell.embeddings
cell_umap = as.data.frame(cell_umap)

cell_umap$imputed_value = imputation_singlecell[rownames(cell_umap),'CD8B']
marker_plot(cell_umap = cell_umap)

cell_umap$imputed_value = imputation_singlecell[rownames(cell_umap),'NCR1']
marker_plot(cell_umap = cell_umap)

cell_umap$imputed_value = imputation_singlecell[rownames(cell_umap),'CXCR5']
marker_plot(cell_umap = cell_umap)
